    "summary": "The invention of the stirrup (c. 2nd–4th centuries AD, likely in Central Asia or northwestern India) was one of the most consequential military innovations in history — a simple device that allowed a mounted warrior to stand up while riding, providing stability for fighting and the ability to deliver a powerful lance charge without being unhorsed. The earliest reliable evidence for true paired metal stirrups comes from the 4th–5th centuries AD in the steppes of Central Asia, though toe stirrups may have appeared in India earlier. The Avars brought the stirrup to Europe in the 6th century AD.\n\nHistorian Lynn White Jr. famously argued in 'Medieval Technology and Social Change' (1962) that the stirrup enabled the development of heavily armored cavalry (knights) as the dominant military force in medieval Europe — and that this military transformation drove the feudal system, as lords granted land (fiefs) to knights in exchange for mounted military service. While White's specific feudalism-from-stirrup thesis has been criticized as oversimplistic, the stirrup's military significance is undeniable: it enabled the armored cavalry charge that became the defining military tactic of medieval warfare in both Europe and the Islamic world. The Mongolian cavalry that conquered Eurasia in the 13th century also depended on the stirrup for their extraordinary mobility and archery on horseback. The stirrup's transformation of mounted warfare rippled through centuries of political and social organization.",
